Diagnosis. Body colour shining black; antennae reddish brown. Fore tarsus black; mid and hind tibiae shining black. Male syntergite 1 + 2 and sternites 1–5 black, tergites 3–5 brownish black; tergite 5 medially declerotized and divided into 2 sclerites; sternite 5 (
Fig. 87
) with a posteromedial comb of 14–15 blunt spines and about 17 spinelike setae in front of it. Gonostyli (
Fig. 85
) asymmetrical, right one with an apically bifurcate inner lobe. Sternite 8 of female (
Fig. 90
) butterfly-shaped; tergite 10 (
Fig. 89
) with 2 long setae on anterior half; body of spermatheca (
Fig. 91
) with small tubercles.

Male abdomen: Syntergite 1 + 2 large, at middle 3 times as long as and slightly wider than tergite 3 , tergite 3 subequal to tergite 4 . Sternite 5 (
Fig. 87
) very similar to that of
M. fanta Roháček & Marshall
, but its deflexed and modified posteromedial lobe with a central comb of about 15 flat spines (thus more than that of
M. fanta
) flanked by laterally directed and apically blunt lobes, and with about 17 thick spine-like setae in front of it (more than that of
M. fanta
). Gonostylus (
Figs. 83, 84, 85
) bilobed, asymmetrical; internal margin with 1 small and 1 large spine; left inner lobe with a pair of slender, apically pointed processes being directed anteriorly and inwardly respectively; right inner lobe with a short apically bifurcate process. Postgonite (
Fig. 86
) slender, thinner and longer than that of
M. fanta
. Phallophore and distiphallus (
Fig. 86
) very similar to that of
M. fanta
.

Female postabdomen: Tergite 6 strongly reduced and light pigmented, medially desclerotized and divided into 2 sclerites. Tergite 8 (
Fig. 89
) tripartite, medially desclerotized, 2 lateral parts dark pigmented. Tergite 10 (
Fig. 89
) posteriorly narrow and anteriorly wide, with posterior two thirds setulose, and anterior half with 2 long setae. Sternite 8 (
Fig. 90
) butterfly-shaped, with posterior half with long setae. Sternite 10 (
Fig. 90
) setulose and dark pigmented on posterior margin; large anterior part medially desclerotized and laterally pale pigmented and with 2 long and 4 medium long setae on its posterior margin; additional paired sclerite between sternite 8 and sternite 10 distinctly developed. Spermathecae (
Fig. 91
) somewhat peanut-shaped, with a shallow apical invagination; sclerotized part of ducts short, half length of spermathecal body, with small tubercles on surface.
